\c 1
\s2 This is a demonstration of some of the new picture positions.
\p
\v 1 There are three new \bd in-line\bd* picture positions, for when the normal
top-left/bottom-right, etc. are not appropriate. These positions are: 
\q1 '\bd here\bd*' (h);  
\q1 '\bd cut-out\bd*' (c) or 'wrapped'  which makes a notch in the
text; 
\q1 '\bd post-paragraph\bd*' (p)  or 'delayed', mainly
for the end of chapters, when there is no verse to put the picture before.

\m Each of these positions
have left and right variations, the 'here' and 'paragraph' have a centred option
too. (e.g. pgpos="hc")
\p The cutout and paragraph options can take a number, indicating a delay by lines (cl2) or paragraphs (pc2)

\p Further there are figure 2 options that place the picture on a page with no text:
\q1 '\bd page\bd*' (P) puts the picture into the normal text area of the page
and 
\q1 `\bd full\bd*' (F) scales the picture to the entirety of the page, e.g. for maps. Note that the caption may be off the bottom of the page if the image is tall.

\p
\v 2 There is no paragraph break in the text here, before the verse that the
pic will attach to. 
\p
\v 3 A new paragraph mid cut-out does not  cause  a problem.  And a cut-out will stop 
without a new paragraph starting. 
\p Notice that the image did not
start at the start of the paragraph, but some lines lower. That is determined by
the digit that follows the side. 
\p Left and right variations have captions the same width as the picture, centred ones get the whole column/page width.
\p
